  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some of the best books on investment?",
  "response": "There are numerous books on investment that are highly regarded for their insights, strategies, and timeless advice. Here are some of the best books on investment:\n\n1. **\"The Intelligent Investor\" by Benjamin Graham** - Often considered the bible of value investing, this book teaches the fundamentals of investing and emphasizes the importance of a disciplined approach.\n\n2. **\"A Random Walk Down Wall Street\" by Burton G. Malkiel** - This book provides an overview of various investment strategies and advocates for a passive investment approach through index funds.\n\n3. **\"Common Stocks and Uncommon Profits\" by Philip Fisher** - Fisher provides insights into growth investing and emphasizes the importance of qualitative factors when selecting stocks.\n\n4. **\"Security Analysis\" by Benjamin Graham and David Dodd** - A more advanced text focusing on the analysis of investments, this book is a foundational work in the field of value investing.\n\n5. **\"Rich Dad Poor Dad\" by Robert T. Kiyosaki** - While not strictly an investment book, it offers valuable lessons on financial literacy, entrepreneurship, and building wealth.\n\n6. **\"The Little Book of Common Sense Investing\" by John C. Bogle** - Written by the founder of Vanguard Group, this book advocates for a simple investment strategy focused on low-cost index funds.\n\n7. **\"One Up On Wall Street\" by Peter Lynch** - Lynch, a successful fund manager, shares his approach to investing and the importance of conducting thorough research.\n\n8. **\"The Essays of Warren Buffett: Lessons for Corporate America\" by Warren Buffett and Lawrence A. Cunningham** - A collection of Buffett's letters to shareholders, this book offers profound investment insights and philosophy.\n\n9. **\"Fooled by Randomness\" by Nassim Nicholas Taleb** - This book explores the role of chance in the financial markets and encourages readers to consider the limits of their knowledge.\n\n10. **\"Principles: Life and Work\" by Ray Dalio** - While not solely focused on investing, Dalio\u2019s principles offer insights into decision-making and risk management applicable to investing.\n\nThese books offer a range of perspectives on investment, from the intricacies of stock selection and market analysis to broader philosophical approaches. Together, they provide a solid foundation for understanding and excelling in the world of investing.",
